<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<worksheet margin="1in" bottom="1.25cm">
  <title>Mean Value Property and Maximum Principle for Harmonic Functions (2D)</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      In this worksheet, you will prove the mean value property for harmonic functions in
      two dimensions using the polar form of the Laplacian, and then apply it to prove
      the maximum principle.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section>
    <title>Harmonicity and Translation</title>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A function <m>u</m> defined on an open set <m>\Omega \subset \mathbb{R}^2</m> is 
          <term>harmonic</term> if <m>\Delta u = u_{xx} + u_{yy} = 0</m>.
          Let <m>a = (a_1,a_2)</m> and define <m>v(x) = u(x + a)</m>.
          Show that if <m>u</m> is harmonic on <m>\Omega</m>,
          then <m>v</m> is harmonic on <m>\Omega - a</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>
          Compute <m>v_x, v_{xx}, v_y, v_{yy}</m> using the chain rule.
        </p>
      </hint>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>u</m> is harmonic on the disk <m>B_R(x_0)</m>.
          Explain why no generality is lost in assuming the disk is centered at <m>0</m>
          when proving the mean value property on circles.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>
          Consider <m>v(x)=u(x + x_0)</m>.  
          Circles centered at <m>x_0</m> become circles centered at <m>0</m>.
        </p>
      </hint>
    </exercise>

  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Mean Value Property via the Polar Laplacian</title>

    <p>
      Assume <m>u \in C^2(B_R(0))</m> and <m>\Delta u = 0</m> in <m>B_R(0)</m>.
    </p>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Define the circular average
        </p>
        <md>
          A(r) = \frac{1}{2\pi} \int_0^{2\pi} u(r,\theta)\, d\theta.
        </md>
        <p>
          Show that this equals the arclength average
        </p>
        <md>
          A(r) = \frac{1}{2\pi r}\int_{\partial B_r(0)} u\, ds.
        </md>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p><m>ds = r\, d\theta</m> on <m>\partial B_r</m>.</p>
      </hint>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>Show that</p>
        <md>
          A'(r) = \frac{1}{2\pi}\int_0^{2\pi} u_r(r,\theta)\, d\theta,
        </md>
        <md>
          A''(r) = \frac{1}{2\pi}\int_0^{2\pi} u_{rr}(r,\theta)\, d\theta.
        </md>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Recall the polar Laplacian:
        </p>
        <md>
          \Delta u = u_{rr} + \frac{1}{r} u_r + \frac{1}{r^2} u_{\theta\theta}.
        </md>
        <p>
          Since <m>u</m> is harmonic, multiply by <m>r^2</m> to obtain:
        </p>
        <md>
          r^2 u_{rr} + r u_r + u_{\theta\theta} = 0.
        </md>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Integrate 
        </p>
        <md>
          r^2 u_{rr} + r u_r + u_{\theta\theta} = 0
        </md>
        <p>
          from <m>0</m> to <m>2\pi</m> in <m>\theta</m> to get:
        </p>
        <md>
          r^2 \int_0^{2\pi} u_{rr}\, d\theta
          + r \int_0^{2\pi} u_r\, d\theta
          + \int_0^{2\pi} u_{\theta\theta}\, d\theta = 0.
        </md>

        <p>Explain why</p>
        <md>
          \int_0^{2\pi} u_{\theta\theta}\, d\theta = 0.
        </md>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>
          <m>\theta \mapsto u(r,\theta)</m> is <m>2\pi</m>–periodic, so
          <m>\int u_{\theta\theta} = u_\theta(2\pi)-u_\theta(0)</m>.
        </p>
      </hint>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>Substitute the formulas for <m>A'(r)</m> and <m>A''(r)</m> to get:</p>
        <md>
          rA''(r) + A'(r) = 0.
        </md>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve this ODE. Show:
        </p>
        <md>
          (r A'(r))' = 0,
        </md>
        <p>
          hence
        </p>
        <md>
          rA'(r) = C.
        </md>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Argue that <m>C = 0</m> using boundedness of <m>A(r)</m> as <m>r \to 0^+</m>.
          Conclude <m>A'(r)=0</m> and <m>A(r)</m> is constant.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>
          Otherwise <m>A(r) = C\ln r + \text{constant}</m> blows up near <m>0</m>.
        </p>
      </hint>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>Show:</p>
        <md>
          \lim_{r\to 0^+} A(r) = u(0).
        </md>
        <p>
          Conclude the mean value property:
        </p>
        <md>
          u(0) = \frac{1}{2\pi}\int_0^{2\pi} u(r,\theta)\, d\theta.
        </md>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

  </section>

  <section>
    <title>The Maximum Principle</title>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>x_0 \in \Omega</m>. Using translation, show:
        </p>
        <md>
          u(x_0) = \frac{1}{2\pi r}\int_{\partial B_r(x_0)} u\, ds
        </md>
        <p>
          whenever <m>\overline{B_r(x_0)} \subset \Omega</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>u</m> attains its maximum at the interior point <m>x_0</m>.
          Show:
        </p>
        <md>
          u(x)=u(x_0) \quad \text{for all } x\in \partial B_r(x_0).
        </md>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>
          An average equals the maximum only if all terms equal the maximum.
        </p>
      </hint>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Show that if <m>u</m> is harmonic on <m>B_r(x_0)</m> and constant on
          <m>\partial B_r(x_0)</m>, then <m>u</m> is constant on the whole disk.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>
          Apply mean value property to <m>w = u - M</m>.
        </p>
      </hint>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Prove the <em>Strong Maximum Principle</em>:
        </p>
        <md>
          \text{If } u \text{ is harmonic on a connected } \Omega \text{ and attains an interior maximum, then } u \text{ is constant.}
        </md>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>
          Show the set where <m>u = u(x_0)</m> is open and closed.
        </p>
      </hint>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Conclude the boundary maximum principle:
        </p>
        <md>
          \max_{\overline{\Omega}} u = \max_{\partial\Omega} u,\qquad
          \min_{\overline{\Omega}} u = \min_{\partial\Omega} u.
        </md>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

  </section>

</worksheet>
